'''Keiron Cunningham''' (born 28 October 1976) is a professional [[rugby league]] coach and former player. A [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]] and [[Wales national rugby league team|Wales]] international representative {{rlp|hk}}, he played his entire professional career at [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]], making nearly 500 appearances for the club between 1994 and 2010 and winning numerous trophies.<ref name="Profile at loverugbyleague.com"/><ref name="Statistics at rugbyleagueproject.org"/> He has been frequently cited as being among the best players in the [[Super League]] history and is widely regarded to be one of St Helens' greatest players of all time.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/feb/08/keiron-cunningham-st-helens-rugby-super-league Cunningham finds permanent place with his Saints]. Theguardian.com (8 February 2009). Retrieved on 31 January 2016.</ref><ref>[https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/super_league/st_helens/8543473.stm Robbie Paul hails Saint Helens Keiron Cunningham the best]. BBC News (1 March 2010). Retrieved on 31 January 2016.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150623100304/http://www.saints.org.uk/pda/playersresults.php?pnum=15154 Keiron Cunningham]. Saints.org.uk. Retrieved on 31 January 2016.</ref><ref>Burke, David (10 October 2007) [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/2323072/Keiron-Cunningham-was-born-to-play-for-Saints.html Keiron Cunningham was born to play for Saints]. Telegraph.co.uk. Retrieved on 31 January 2016.</ref>

The youngest of ten siblings, two of his brothers, [[Eddie Cunningham]] and [[Tommy Cunningham (rugby league)|Tommy Cunningham]], also played for St Helens. Keiron Cunningham was born five months after his brother Eddie won a Rugby League [[Challenge Cup]] winner's medal for St Helens against [[Widnes Vikings|Widnes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/wales/1480873.stm|title=Big brother rules out Keiron claim|date=8 August 2001|website=BBC.co.uk|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=22 November 2010}}</ref>

Following his retirement as a player, Cunningham remained at St Helens as an assistant coach, and was head coach of the club between 2015 and 2017.<ref name="Coach Statistics at rugbyleagueproject.org"/><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/39554106 Keiron Cunningham: St Helens part company with head coach]</ref>

==Playing career==
In 1993, on his 17th birthday, Cunningham signed for his hometown club [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]] from [[Wigan St Judes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cunningham backs league cause|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/1477875.stm|website=BBC Sport|access-date=10 December 2014|date=7 August 2001}}</ref> He made his début in the [[1994–95 Rugby Football League season]], and soon established himself as a world class hooker, renowned for his dynamic running from [[Rugby league positions#dummy half|dummy half]] and ability to poach tries from short distances. He represented both [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]] and [[Wales national rugby league team|Wales]] in international matches, qualifying for Wales because of a Welsh grandfather.

Keiron Cunningham played {{rlp|hk}}, and scored a [[Try (rugby)|try]] in [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]]' 16-25 defeat by [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]] in the [[1995–96 League Cup (rugby league)|1995–96 Regal Trophy]] Final during the [[1995–96 Rugby Football League season|1995–96]] at [[John Smith's Stadium|Alfred McAlpine Stadium]], [[Huddersfield]] on Saturday 13 January 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wigan.rlfans.com/news.php?readmore=2976|title=13th January 1996: St Helens 16 Wigan 25 (Regal Trophy Final)|publisher=wigan.rlfans.com|date=31 December 2014|access-date=1 January 2015|archive-date=7 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007005311/http://wigan.rlfans.com/news.php?readmore=2976|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Cunningham played for St Helens at hooker in the [[1996 Challenge Cup]] Final, scoring a try in the second half of the match and helping his team to a 40-32 victory over the [[Bradford Bulls]].<ref>{{cite web|title=steveprescottfoundation.co.uk|url=http://www.steveprescottfoundation.co.uk/About/StevePrescottStats.aspx|work=Steve Prescott Stats|publisher=Steve Prescott Foundation|access-date=3 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808052156/http://www.steveprescottfoundation.co.uk/About/StevePrescottStats.aspx|archive-date=8 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the end of 1996's [[Super League I]], Cunningham was named at hooker in the 1996 [[Super League Dream Team]]. Cunningham played for St Helens at {{rlp|hk}} in their [[1999 Super League Grand Final]] victory over the [[Bradford Bulls]]. Also in 1999 he was the only British player voted into the World XIII.<ref>{{cite news
| title = World Cup Star - Keiron Cunningham
| work = sportinglife.com
| publisher = sportinglife.com
| year = 2000
|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/rugbyleague/worldcup2000/star_men/story_get.dor?STORY_NAME=Sporting_Life/00/10/05/manual_135348.html
| access-date = 4 February 2010
| archive-date = 4 June 2011
| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604215022/http://www.sportinglife.com/rugbyleague/worldcup2000/star_men/story_get.dor?STORY_NAME=Sporting_Life/00/10/05/manual_135348.html
| url-status = dead
}}</ref>
[[File:Keiron Cunningham Saints.JPG|200px|thumb|right|Cunningham playing for St Helens in 2010]]
Cunningham played for St Helens at {{rlp|hk}} in their [[2000 Super League Grand Final]] victory against the [[Wigan Warriors]].  As [[Super League V]] champions, St Helens played against [[2000 NRL season|2000 NRL]] Premiers, the [[Brisbane Broncos]] in the [[2001 World Club Challenge]]. Cunningham played at {{rlp|hk}} in Saints' victory.

Cunningham played for St. Helens at {{rlp|hk}} in their [[2002 Super League Grand Final]] victory against the [[Bradford Bulls]].

Over the course of his career, Cunningham rejected offers from the [[Welsh Rugby Union]], [[England national rugby union team|England Rugby Union]], and from various Australian rugby league clubs, instead choosing to remain with his hometown team. In 2006 Cunningham was named as captain of St. Helens following the persistent injuries and subsequent retirement of [[Paul Sculthorpe]]. Cunningham played for St. Helens at {{rlp|hk}} in their [[2006 Challenge Cup]] Final victory against the [[Huddersfield Giants]].  St Helens reached the [[2006 Super League Grand final]] to be contested against [[Hull F.C.|Hull FC]], and Cunningham played at {{rlp|hk}}, scoring a [[Try (rugby)|try]] in Saints' 26-4 victory. As 2006 Super League champions, St Helens faced 2006 NRL Premiers the [[Brisbane Broncos]] in the [[2007 World Club Challenge]]. Cunningham played from the interchange bench in Saints' 18-14 victory.

He played in the [[2009 Super League Grand Final]] defeat by the [[Leeds Rhinos]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news|last=AFP|title=Leeds makes it Super League hat-trick|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-10-11/leeds-makes-it-super-league-hat-trick/1098564|access-date=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] News|date=11 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113060836/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-10-11/leeds-makes-it-super-league-hat-trick/1098564|archive-date=13 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Fletcher|first=Paul|title=St Helens 10-18 Leeds Rhinos|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/8290503.stm|access-date=22 November 2019|work=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2009}}</ref>
[[File:Keiron Cunningham.JPG|thumb|left|Keiron Cunningham warming up for St Helens in 2010]]
In 2010, Cunningham announced that he would be retiring from rugby league following the culmination of 2010's [[Super League XV]].<ref name="Retirement">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/super_league/st_helens/8481451.stm|title=Cunningham looking to end on a high|publisher=BBC|date=26 January 2010|access-date=26 February 2010}}</ref> 2010 also marked the last year at St Helens' [[Knowsley Road]] ground before moving to a new stadium. It was, in fact, Kieron Cunningham who scored the last try ever at the prestigious ground in his penultimate match. However, despite a memorable 2010 play-offs for Cunningham, there was to be no fairytale ending as his last game ended in defeat against arch rivals the [[Wigan Warriors]] in the [[2010 Super League Grand Final]].

He finished his career with 496 appearances for St Helens,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Slater|first1=Gary|title=Michael Maguire plots new Wigan dynasty following Grand Final win over St Helens|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/8040214/Michael-Maguire-plots-new-Wigan-dynasty-following-Grand-Final-win-over-St-Helens.html|website=The Telegraph|access-date=10 December 2014|date=3 October 2010}}</ref> scoring 175 tries.

During his career he won five Super League Championships, seven Challenge Cup Winners Medals and two World Club Challenge Winners medals, was named in the [[Super League Dream Team]] on six occasions,<ref name="2008 engage Super League Dream Team">{{cite web|url=http://www.superleague.co.uk/article.php?id=11755 |title=2008 engage Super League Dream Team |publisher=Super League |date=15 September 2008 |access-date=26 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721195910/http://www.superleague.co.uk/article.php?id=11755 |archive-date=21 July 2010 }}</ref> and in July 2007 [[Rugby League World]] magazine ranked him as the greatest player of the [[Super League]] era.

Following a supporters' poll featuring the likes of [[Tom van Vollenhoven]] and [[Alex Murphy (rugby league)|Alex Murphy]], Cunningham was chosen to be cast as a bronze statue outside of [[Langtree Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/news/9311164.Cunningham_statue_moves_to_new_stadium/
|title=Cunningham statue moves to new stadium|work=St Helens Star|date=18 October 2011 |access-date=25 October 2012}}</ref> The statue was unveiled on Chalon Way opposite the Glass House pub in March 2010<ref>{{cite news|last=Kilmurray|first=Andrew|title=Saints' Keiron Cunningham 'humbled' by bronze statue|url=http://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/news/5042659.Cunningham_statue_is_unveiled|access-date=14 January 2014|newspaper=St Helens Star|date=4 March 2010}}</ref> and was relocated to the stadium following its completion in October 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Keiron Cunningham statue moves to new Saints rugby league stadium|url=http://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/news/9311164.Cunningham_statue_moves_to_new_stadium|access-date=14 January 2014|newspaper=St Helens Star|date=18 October 2011}}</ref>

==Coaching career==
[[File:Cunningham statue, Totally Wicked Stadium, St Helens.jpg|Statue at St Helens stadium|thumb|right]]
Following his retirement as a player, Cunningham took up an assistant coaching role in the strength and conditioning department at St Helens. After the sacking of [[Royce Simmons]] in 2012 he was appointed assistant head coach of St Helens, working alongside temporary head coach Mike Rush.

On Monday 20 October 2014, Cunningham was appointed as [[head coach]] of [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]]. He appointed former Saints teammate [[Sean Long]] to assist him for his role.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/nov/17/sean-long-return-st-helens-assistant-coach Sean Long returns to St Helens as Keiron Cunningham’s assistant coach| Sport]. The Guardian (17 November 2014). Retrieved on 31 January 2016.</ref> On 10 April 2017 it was announced on the BBC North West Today lunchtime bulletin that Cunningham had been sacked after 24 years associated with the club.

